My first monitor had a strip on the left side that was slightly discolored under certain circumstances, and could sometimes flicker

I drove myself mad trying to prove to CS that it was faulty.  Luckily an indie game had a particular spot that caused the strip to freak the frick out.  It flickered so badly that I could capture it on my phone and it would be clear to anyone.

While I did have to pay for shipping the first time around, when my monitor came back and was broken (small section of frame broken, panel damaged, nice little colored spider web when I turned it on xD)
When I reported the damage to CS, within 30 minutes I had a return shipping label, and I was sent a brand new monitor super fast
I can just imagine their CS finding this out: "We just sent this person a new monitor. Turns out it was broken too!"
While I was understandly frustrated / upset with the broken return, the new one made me veeeeeeeeery happy.
Tbh, small details are my kinda thing
And this was that, a small detail
But that can be both positive and negative
You could call it a shadow, but it was very picky about when it was visible
The flickering, though, that was more noticeable when it did happen
And not the greatest for your eyes either
And the flickering is what made the defect more apparent
I'm not sure what the issue was, either
It's like it couldn't supply light correctly
It's worth mentioning that the shape changed over time
So those three things together made me go ahead with an rma
This panel is near perfect, too

My previous monitor (Have yet to get a new one) ended up not being produced anymore. The power supply stopped working (Replaced it). Turns out the port in which you connect the PSU to the monitor was fried
I'd argue that the backlight bleed is better than the original, and while it does have some dim pixels, they're pretty hard to notice, and are more likely to be confused with dust than anything else
I'd rather that than spiderwebbing and constant flickering
The flickering only happened during loading screens in WoW and during gameplay in that ONE indie title
But it was enough for me to be convinced it was a problem worth fixing :)
At least you ended up doing just that
Btw, can confirm, larger area vs concentrated discoloration is more bearable when it comes to blb ;)
This monitor seems to have more backlight bleed than the original, but the original had pretty serious (relatively speaking) bleed in the lower right corner
It could discolor very dark scenes
Eh, it comes with the territory
Until the pixels themselves emit the light, it's just an unfortunate consequence
Anywho, consider me a fan of ViewSonic
They also have a very generous defective pixel policy
Last I checked, all the matters is pixel count.  Density / screen section does not apply

Just watched Louis Rossman spend 9.5 minutes telling all his viewers, customers, and anyone else who gives a shit, "I told you so"
Well, what do you expect?  His businesses thrives on doing board-level repairs for crApple products
And crApple have finally done it
They've made a motherboard with an unrepairable part.
Their new laptops have a T2 chip that is literally unreplaceable
It's pulling doubletime, too, and doing the work that used to be delegated to 2 chips

And apparently these chips have programming that is board specific, so if it dies, there's nothing you can do but buy a new board.  And since there is NO data recovery possibilities with this board, if that chip goes, you better have backed up your shit :

Best part?  This laptop is 3 months old, and Apple said the warranty wasn't valid because of liquid damage.  Well Louis gave us a REEEEAAAAAAAL close look at that board all over the place, and with a microscope.
